1. Enhance the Test Suite (tests/)

· Unit Tests: Add tests/unit/test_sha2.c for edge cases (empty input, exact block size, multi-block).
· Property-Based Tests: Use a framework like quickcheck for C (or write simple random tests). For example: hash(x) == hash(x), or test incremental vs. one-shot hashing.

2. Set Up GitHub Actions (.github/workflows/)

· ci.yml: Runs on every push/pull request.
  · Build the library with -Wall -Wextra -Werror -pedantic.
  · Run all unit tests and KATs.
  · Run basic sanitizers (AddressSanitizer, UndefinedBehaviorSanitizer).
· fuzz.yml: Can be scheduled (e.g., nightly) or run on demand.
  · Sets up a fuzzing job using libFuzzer.
  · The target is tests/fuzz/fuzz_sha2.c – a simple function that takes fuzzer input and calls crypto_hash_sha256.

Example fuzz_sha2.c snippet:

```c
#include "../src/primitives/hash/sha2.h"
#include <stdint.h>
#include <stddef.h>

int LLVMFuzzerTestOneInput(const uint8_t *data, size_t size) {
    uint8_t hash[32];
    // The fuzzer will provide random data/lengths. We test for crashes.
    crypto_hash_sha256(hash, data, size);
    // Optional: Compare with a known-good library for correctness?
    return 0;
}